Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Workplace safety in hazardous environments like construction sites and industrial plants is crucial to prevent accidents and injuries. One of the most important safety measures is ensuring workers wear safety helmets, which protect against head injuries from falling objects and machinery. Non-compliance with helmet regulations increases the risk of serious injuries or fatalities, making effective monitoring essential, especially in large-scale operations where manual oversight is prone to errors and inefficiency.

To overcome these challenges, SafeGuard Corp plans to develop an automated image analysis system capable of detecting whether workers are wearing safety helmets. This system will improve safety enforcement, ensuring compliance and reducing the risk of head injuries. By automating helmet monitoring, SafeGuard aims to enhance efficiency, scalability, and accuracy, ultimately fostering a safer work environment while minimizing human error in safety oversight.

Objective¶

As a data scientist at SafeGuard Corp, you are tasked with developing an image classification model that classifies images into one of two categories:

  • With Helmet: Workers wearing safety helmets.
  • Without Helmet: Workers not wearing safety helmets.

Data Description¶

The dataset consists of 631 images, equally divided into two categories:

  • With Helmet: 311 images showing workers wearing helmets.
  • Without Helmet: 320 images showing workers not wearing helmets.

Dataset Characteristics:

  • Variations in Conditions: Images include diverse environments such as construction sites, factories, and industrial settings, with variations in lighting, angles, and worker postures to simulate real-world conditions.
  • Worker Activities: Workers are depicted in different actions such as standing, using tools, or moving, ensuring robust model learning for various scenarios.

def plot_images(images,labels):
  num_classes=2                # Number of Classes
  categories=np.unique(labels)
  keys=dict(labels['Label'])     # Obtaing the unique classes from y_train
  rows = 3                       # Defining number of rows=3
  cols = 4                       # Defining number of columns=4
  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))   # Defining the figure size to 10x8
  for i in range(cols):
      for j in range(rows):
          random_index = np.random.randint(0, len(labels))   # Generating random indices from the data and plotting the images
          ax = fig.add_subplot(rows, cols, i * rows + j + 1) # Adding subplots with 3 rows and 4 columns
          ax.imshow(images[random_index, :])  # Plotting the image
          ax.set_title(keys[random_index])
  plt.show()

Model Building¶

Utility Functions¶

In [22]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using statsmodels
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred = model.predict(predictors).reshape(-1)>0.5

    target = target.to_numpy().reshape(-1)


    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame({"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1 Score": f1,},index=[0],)

    return df_perf
In [23]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model,predictors,target,ml=False):
    """
    Function to plot the confusion matrix

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    ml: To specify if the model used is an sklearn ML model or not (True means ML model)
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred = model.predict(predictors).reshape(-1)>0.5

    target = target.to_numpy().reshape(-1)

    # Plotting the Confusion Matrix using confusion matrix() function which is also predefined tensorflow module
    confusion_matrix = tf.math.confusion_matrix(target,pred)
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
    sns.heatmap(
        confusion_matrix,
        annot=True,
        linewidths=.4,
        fmt="d",
        square=True,
        ax=ax
    )
    plt.show()

Model 1 : Simple Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)¶

In [24]:
# Define the CNN model

model_cnn = Sequential([
    # 1st Convolutional Layer
    Conv2D(filters=4, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(64, 64, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)),

    # 2nd Convolutional Layer
    Conv2D(filters=8, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)),

    # Flatten before Fully Connected Layers
    Flatten(),

    # Fully Connected Layers
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(32, activation='relu'),

    # Output Layer (for binary classification)
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

# Compile the model
model_cnn.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Summary
model_cnn.summary()

Model 4: (VGG-16 (Base + FFNN + Data Augmentation)¶

  • In most of the real-world case studies, it is challenging to acquire a large number of images and then train CNNs.

  • To overcome this problem, one approach we might consider is Data Augmentation.

  • CNNs have the property of translational invariance, which means they can recognise an object even if its appearance shifts translationally in some way. - Taking this attribute into account, we can augment the images using the techniques listed below

    • Horizontal Flip (should be set to True/False)
    • Vertical Flip (should be set to True/False)
    • Height Shift (should be between 0 and 1)
    • Width Shift (should be between 0 and 1)
    • Rotation (should be between 0 and 180)
    • Shear (should be between 0 and 1)
    • Zoom (should be between 0 and 1) etc.

Remember, data augmentation should not be used in the validation/test data set.

In [53]:
train_datagen_aug = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255,            # Normalize pixel values
    horizontal_flip=True,      # True or False
    vertical_flip=False,       # True or False
    height_shift_range=0.2,    # Between 0 and 1 (e.g., 0.2 = 20% shift)
    width_shift_range=0.2,     # Between 0 and 1
    rotation_range=30,         # Between 0 and 180 degrees
    shear_range=0.2,           # Between 0 and 1
    zoom_range=0.2,            # Between 0 and 1
    fill_mode='nearest'        # How to fill pixels after transform
)

Actionable Insights & Recommendations¶

  1. Model Performance Analysis Based on our comprehensive evaluation of four different models for helmet detection:

    • The VGG-16 (Base + FFNN) model demonstrated the best overall performance with a perfect F1 score on the validation set while producing very accurate probabilities on both class labels.
    • This model effectively balances precision and recall, which is crucial for safety applications where both false positives and false negatives have significant consequences.
    • The addition of a Feed-Forward Neural Network (FFNN) head to the VGG-16 base model improved probability scores by allowing the model to learn more complex patterns specific to helmet detection.
    • Data augmentation techniques further enhanced the model's robustness by exposing it to a wider variety of image variations during training.

  2. Business Value and Implementation SafeGuard Corp can leverage this helmet detection model to:

    • Automate safety compliance monitoring across construction sites and industrial facilities
    • Reduce the risk of workplace injuries by identifying non-compliance in real-time
    • Lower operational costs associated with manual safety inspections
    • Generate data-driven insights on safety compliance trends across different sites and times

  3. Deployment Strategy For effective deployment, we recommend:

    • Integration with existing CCTV systems for real-time monitoring
    • Development of a user-friendly dashboard for safety officers to review alerts and compliance metrics
    • Implementation of a notification system to alert supervisors of safety violations
    • Phased rollout starting with high-risk areas before expanding to all facilities
    • Regular model retraining with new data to improve accuracy over time

  4. Limitations and Future Improvements Current limitations and potential enhancements include:

    • The model may struggle with unusual lighting conditions or partially visible workers
    • Future versions could incorporate:
      • Multi-class classification to detect different types of safety equipment (e.g., vests, goggles)
      • Object detection capabilities to identify multiple workers in a single frame
      • Edge deployment for processing without internet connectivity
      • Integration with other safety systems for comprehensive workplace safety monitoring

  5. ROI and Business Impact Implementation of this automated helmet detection system is expected to deliver:

    • considerable reduction in safety incidents related to head injuries
    • substantial decrease in time spent on manual safety compliance monitoring
    • Potential insurance premium reductions due to improved safety measures
    • Enhanced company reputation as a safety-conscious employer
    • Compliance with regulatory requirements and avoidance of potential fines

By implementing this AI-powered helmet detection system, SafeGuard Corp can transform its approach to workplace safety, moving from reactive to proactive safety management while improving operational efficiency and worker protection.
